21. pergraecamz'm'] i. e. ‘play the profligate.’ The stern and austere old Romans, when they first became acquainted with the Greeks in Southern Italy, would naturally be shocked by a mode of life so repugnant to their own habits and prejudices‚ and hence when they wished to express that a man was indulging in dissolute prac- tices and embarked on a profligate career, they said that he was ‘playing the Greek.'
